Currently Cloud users cannot display wallboards on separate TVs/monitors without logging in manually and loading the Wallboard. 

Ideally users would be able to use a URL like the one below to embed their user credentials and have the Wallboard display and update without manually logging in:

{code}
{http://your-jira-url.com}/login.jsp?os_username={wallboard-user}&os_password={wallboard-password}&os_destination=plugins/servlet/Wallboard/?dashboardId={dashboard-id}
{code}

h3. Preconditions:	
1. Go to link https://8wines.com;
2. Go through authorization.
h3. Steps to Reproduce:
1.	Select: “My Profile”;
2.	Click on “Выберите файл”;
3.	Select incorrect data type (for example: “.exe” instead .jpg);
4.	Click on Save.
h3. Expected result:
Message about incorrect data type.
h3. Actual result:	
No any message about incorrect data type.

h3. Preconditions:
1.	Go to link https://8wines.com;
2.	Go through authorization.
h3. Steps to Reproduce:
1.	Select: “My Profile”;
2.	Change email address;
3.	Click on Save.
h3. Expected result:
1.	The message says that information about email changing has sent to our new and old email address;
2.	Messages about email changing (in new and old email).
h3. Actual result:
Email has changed without notice to new and old email address.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-12693].
  {panel}

When viewing our Service Desk issues as a Kanban Board in JIRA we've noticed that lately some of the issues have lots of dots at the bottom of the card, even if they are brand new issues.

When hovering over the dots with the mouse a message pops up saying "16578 days in this column".

I try to create a Kanban or Scrum board programmatically using JIRA Software Java API. I use this code:
{code:java}
String boardName = "B1";
Long filterId = 10001L;
ApplicationUser user = ComponentAccessor.getJiraAuthenticationContext().getLoggedInUser();
 
RapidView rv = RapidView.builder().name(boardName).owner(user.getUsername())
        .savedFilterId(filterId).cardColorStrategy(CardColorStrategy.ISSUE_TYPE)
        .swimlaneStrategy(SwimlaneStrategy.EPIC).showDaysInColumn(false)
        .sprintMarkersMigrated(false).sprintSupportEnabled(false).build();
RapidViewManager rvManager = new RapidViewManagerImpl();
ServiceOutcome<RapidView> so = rvManager.create(rv, user, RapidViewPreset.KANBAN);
{code}
 
Unfortunately I get _NullPointerException_:
{code:java}
java.lang.NullPointerException
    at com.atlassian.greenhopper.manager.rapidview.RapidViewManagerImpl.create(RapidViewManagerImpl.java:187)
    at com.atlassian.tutorial.helloworld.MyTestServlet.doGet(MyTestServlet.java:92)
    at javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet.service(HttpServlet.java:620)
    at javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet.service(HttpServlet.java:727)
        ...
{code}

I tried passing _RapidViewPreset.SCRUM_, calling _...builder().id(null)..._ and passing other values to builder methods. The result is always the same, i.e. NPE.

As I call all the methods of the rapid view builder and I cannot find any property which I should set yet, I suppose it is a bug in the _RapidViewManagerImpl_ class.

h3. Problem Definition
Today, the "Days in column" feature from Kanban boards seems to be cumulative.
Steps to replicate:
- Drag an issue to a specific column (column 1);
- After one day, drag it to another column (column 2);
- Again, after one day, drag it back to the same column from the beginning (column 1);
The "Days in column" information will sum the day from the first time with the time spent there now.

h3. Suggested Solution
In case that's an expected behaviour in JIRA Agile, clarify this information in the [Configuring Columns|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/AGILE/Configuring+Columns] documentation.

h3. Summary
 * In the Release Burndown report, if the "Active" period of two or more sprints that contain issues under a given Version overlap, all issues will be displayed under one single, latest sprint.
 * Having multiple overlapping Sprints on a single Agile board can happen if:
 ** "Parallel Sprints" is enabled;
 ** The board contains issues from other boards;

h3. Steps to Reproduce
h5. With "Parallel Sprints" enabled
 # Enable "Parallel Sprints", as described [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/agile/jira-agile-resources/jira-agile-faq/how-do-i-have-multiple-or-parallel-sprints-running-at-the-same-time];
 # Create a project;
 # Create a version under that project;
 # Create a board with all issues from the project;
 # Create two or more Sprints, associating one or more issues of the board per Sprint;
 # Estimate all issues and set the created version as "Fix Version" of the issues;
 # Start all created Sprints;
 # Close one or more issues in each Sprint;
 # Complete all Sprints;

h3. Starting Multiple Active Sprints *without* 'Parallel Sprints'
 # Have an existing board (Board 1) with a filter showing: "project = SSP ORDER BY Rank ASC"
 # Create a second board (Board 2) with a filter covering just a limited set of issues in the SSP project: "issue in (SSP-1,SSP-2) ORDER BY Rank ASC"
 # Now start a Sprint in Board 1, then Board 2
 # Refresh Board 1, notice that there are two active Sprints showing

h3. Expected Result
 * Release Burndown report will show list of issue respectively to its own sprint

h3. Actual Result
 * Release Burndown report shows all the issues under the Sprint last closed.
 !agile.png|thumbnail!
 !agile1.png|thumbnail!

h3. Workaround
h5. If due to Parallel Sprints
 * Avoid using parallel sprint
